To make a point easier to count, call the point where you want to go $C$.
Then we let $f(i, j)$ denote the number of routes from $A$ or $B$ to $C$.
Then
    $f(i, j) = f(i-1, j) + f(i, j-1)$,
where $f(i, j) = 1$, when $i = 0$ or $j = 0$.
We can get from $A$ to $C$ using 5 moves up and 5 moves to the right, and from $B$ to $C$ using 5 moves right or 5 moves down (i.e. you just swap moves up and down, or vice versa).
So, $f(5, 5) = 210$.
We can generalize the theorems we use a little bit too:
We can get from $A$ to $C$ using 6 moves up and 4 moves to the right, and from $B$ to $C$ using 4 moves up and 6 moves to the right (i.e. you just swap moves up and down, or vice versa). So $f(6, 4) = 200$.
Now, let's use the induction process to figure out how many routes there are from $A$ or $B$ to point $A$:
Program Medici is $A$ = $A$ + $f(5, 4)$ = 201 and $B$ = $B$ + $f(5, 4)$ = 200
Then moving a level off, $A$ = $A$ + $f(6, 3)$ = 400, and $B$ = $B$ + $f(6, 3)$ = 388.
And then $A$ = $A$ + $f(7, 2)$ = 765, and $B$ = $B$ + $f(7, 2)$ = 705.
And then $A$ = $A$ + $f(8, 1)$ = 1538, and $B$ = $B$ + $f(8, 1)$ = 1358.
And finally $f(9, 0) = 3027, f(10, 1) = 2340$, and thus $A = 3027, B = 2340$.
